This paper is about detecting unknown intents in dialogue systems using deep learning techniques. The primary focus is on natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) methods, which are typically covered in the cs.CL (Computation and Language) sub-category. The paper also uses deep learning techniques, which are covered in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves novelty detection, which is a subfield of ML and AI, covered in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The paper also uses a density-based outlier detection algorithm, which is a technique used in neural networks and deep learning, covered in the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses a bidirectional LSTM network, which is a type of recurrent neural network (RNN) commonly used in NLP and computer vision, covered in the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category.
